<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>How does hyperinflation affect the demand for money?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increases money demand as prices rise</option>
            <option letter="b">Decreases money demand as people spend quickly</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on money demand</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects foreign currency demand</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>During hyperinflation, people reduce their demand for money because they try to spend it quickly before it loses more value, leading to an increased velocity of money.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to structural unemployment during rapid technological change?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Decreases as new jobs are created</option>
            <option letter="b">Increases as skills become obsolete</option>
            <option letter="c">Remains constant despite changes</option>
            <option letter="d">Becomes cyclical unemployment</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Rapid technological change often increases structural unemployment as existing workers' skills become obsolete and don't match the requirements of newly created jobs.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in investment spending affect the LRAS curve?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Shifts LRAS left</option>
            <option letter="b">Shifts LRAS right</option>
            <option letter="c">Moves along existing LRAS</option>
            <option letter="d">Has no effect on LRAS</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in investment spending increases the economy's capital stock, which expands productive capacity and shifts the Long-Run Aggregate Supply curve to the right.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What is the primary difference between nominal and real values in economics?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Nominal includes taxes, real doesn't</option>
            <option letter="b">Nominal includes imports, real doesn't</option>
            <option letter="c">Nominal is in current prices, real is adjusted for inflation</option>
            <option letter="d">Nominal is adjusted for population, real isn't</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>The primary difference is that nominal values are measured in current prices, while real values are adjusted for inflation to show actual changes in purchasing power or quantity.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
